         <abstract>
            <p>When the physical asset consumption that American industry is now reporting on the basis of historical costs incurred at lower price levels is translated into current reproduction costs, the results are startling: adjusted after-tax profits in 1973 are only half as large as reported. In constant dollars, adjusted 1973 profits were only slightly over half 1965 profits, and retained earnings were down nearly 90 per cent.</p>
          </abstract>
